% You are an expert Python engineer. Your goal is to write the pdd/cli_detector.py module.

% Role & Scope
Detects and bootstraps agentic CLI harnesses (Claude CLI, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, Antigravity CLI, OpenCode CLI) required for `pdd fix`, `pdd change`, `pdd bug`, and `pdd setup`. The primary entry point `detect_and_bootstrap_cli()` presents a numbered table of CLIs with install/key status, lets the user select one or more, and walks through installation and credential configuration for each. The legacy `detect_cli_tools()` function is preserved for backward compatibility. **Antigravity migration (Issue #1152):** Both Antigravity (`agy`) and legacy Gemini (`gemini`) are detected as candidate binaries for the Google provider; `agy` is preferred where present because Google announced consumer-tier Gemini CLI cutoff on 2026-06-18. Both remain installable during the migration so users keep a safe rollback path.

% Requirements

1. Dataclass: `CliBootstrapResult` with fields `cli_name: str`, `provider: str`, `cli_path: str`, `api_key_configured: bool`, `skipped: bool` (default False). All strings default to empty.

2. Function: `detect_and_bootstrap_cli() -> List[CliBootstrapResult]` — Phase 1 entry point for `pdd setup`.
   a. Print a step banner via `_print_step_banner()` imported from `pdd.setup_tool`.
   b. Detect all configured CLIs via `shutil.which()` with fallback to common paths (~/.local/bin, /usr/local/bin, /opt/homebrew/bin, ~/.antigravity/bin) and nvm node version directories. The Google provider gets two candidate binaries: `agy` (Antigravity, preferred) and `gemini` (legacy fallback); detection records whichever is present and exposes both to the selection table when both are installed so the user can see the rollback path.
   c. Provider mappings: openai->codex, google->{agy preferred, gemini fallback}, anthropic->claude, opencode->opencode. Table order: Codex CLI, Antigravity CLI (`agy`), Gemini CLI (`gemini`), Claude CLI, OpenCode CLI. Codex is listed first in setup because it is the recommended no-API-key credential for direct/local `llm_invoke` calls; this table does not change runtime agentic provider order, which is controlled by `agentic_common` / `PDD_AGENTIC_PROVIDER`. Both Antigravity and Gemini entries map to the `google` provider; the selection table groups them under "Google (Gemini family)" and notes that `agy` is the preferred Antigravity binary while `gemini` remains the legacy rollback ahead of Google's 2026-06-18 consumer-tier Gemini CLI cutoff.
   d. Print a numbered selection table showing install status and credential status per CLI, with aligned columns. Credential status reports: API key set (green ✓), or stored OAuth/subscription/config credential configured (green ✓), or no credentials (red ✗).
   e. Accept comma-separated numeric input (e.g. "1,3"). Default to best available (installed+any-credential > installed > Codex). Any credential includes either API key OR stored OAuth login. "q"/"n" returns a skipped result.
   f. For each selected CLI, process install/credential/test in sequence. On skip or failure of one CLI, continue to the next.
   g. Install step: prompt user, run the appropriate installer via subprocess if accepted. For npm-distributed CLIs check npm availability first. Install commands are `npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`, `npm install -g @openai/codex`, `npm install -g @google/gemini-cli`, and `npm install -g opencode-ai`. The Antigravity CLI (`agy`) is NOT distributed via npm — its install hint is `curl -fsSL https://antigravity.google/cli/install.sh | bash` (or the user's preferred mechanism); detection MUST NOT shell out to that URL automatically. Pipe to `bash`, not `sh` — the installer uses `set -o pipefail` which fails under dash (the default `/bin/sh` on Debian/Ubuntu). Surface the curl command in the prompt and let the user copy/run it themselves so credential prompts and shell init are not bypassed.
   h. Credential step: skip entirely when the CLI already has a stored OAuth/subscription/config credential (`_has_cli_oauth(cli)` returns True for the CLI-specific location/config: anthropic from `~/.claude/.credentials.json` or `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/credentials.json` or macOS keychain `Claude Code-credentials` or `CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN` env; legacy gemini from `~/.gemini/oauth_creds.json`; Antigravity `agy` from either a populated `~/.gemini/antigravity-cli/oauth_creds.json` OR the keyring-backed subscription sign-in marker (`~/.gemini/antigravity-cli/cache/onboarding.json` declares onboarding complete and `~/.gemini/google_accounts.json` declares an active account); both Google CLIs from Vertex env auth (`GOOGLE_GENAI_USE_VERTEXAI=true` plus `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS`, `GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT`, `VERTEXAI_PROJECT`, or `VERTEX_PROJECT`); openai from a Codex subscription login at `$CODEX_HOME/auth.json` (honor `CODEX_HOME`, default `~/.codex`; resolve the path by reusing `codex_subscription._codex_auth_path()` rather than hardcoding `~/.codex/auth.json`) or a non-empty `CODEX_API_KEY` env var (Issue #1318 — Codex/ChatGPT subscription is now a direct/local `llm_invoke` credential path, so a fresh `codex login` with no `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` must show openai credentials configured); opencode from `~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json` only when it parses to non-empty provider credentials, or from global/project/env OpenCode config only when parsed JSON/JSONC declares a usable provider/model with resolvable auth or explicit local/no-key provider semantics). Issue #813 round-9 hardening: the anthropic/google file checks MUST parse the credentials JSON shape and require real token/config keys where applicable — a bare size check (`stat().st_size > 0`) false-positives on stale, corrupt, or logged-out files that still contain bytes but no usable token, then `pdd setup` skips the API-key prompt and leaves the user with no working credential. The shape parse must swallow `OSError` and `JSONDecodeError` and return False. Match the parse style of the google/openai/opencode branches (they parse for known token/config keys rather than file size alone). Issue #813 root: prompting OAuth-only users for an API key here pushes them into the exact stale-key workflow this fix exists to make safe. When OAuth/config is detected without an API key, print a green confirmation that the stored credential/config will be used (for anthropic, also mention `PDD_KEEP_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=1` as the opt-out for forcing API-key billing). Only when neither API key nor OAuth/config is present, prompt for an API key for normal providers, save to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` with shell-appropriate syntax, add source line to RC file, set in `os.environ`. For OpenCode specifically, do NOT prompt for an `OPENCODE_API_KEY` because no such dedicated key exists; print a dim hint to run `opencode auth login`, configure a usable `~/.config/opencode/opencode.json` or project `opencode.json`, or set an underlying provider env var plus `OPENCODE_MODEL=provider/model`. Include the OpenCode docs URL `https://opencode.ai/docs/providers`.
   i. CLI test step (always runs, cannot be skipped): run `cli --version`, fall back to `--help` if that fails.
   j. Handle KeyboardInterrupt/EOFError at every input prompt gracefully.
   k. Return list of results; if empty, return `[CliBootstrapResult(skipped=True)]`.

3. Function: `detect_cli_tools() -> None` — legacy detection. For each CLI: show found/not-found status, cross-reference API keys, offer installation for missing CLIs that have matching keys.

4. Shell detection: detect from `SHELL` env var (default "bash"). Map to RC file: zsh->.zshrc, bash->.bashrc, fish->~/.config/fish/config.fish.

5. API key file management: create `~/.pdd/` if needed. Write keys to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` (append, dedup by key name using regex). Add source line to RC file if not present. Shell syntax: bash/zsh use `export K=V`, fish uses `set -gx K V`. Source syntax: bash/zsh use `source path`, fish uses `test -f path ; and source path`.

6. Google provider: API keys are binary-aware — `GOOGLE_API_KEY` is consumed by both `agy` and legacy `gemini`; `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` is consumed ONLY by `agy`; `GEMINI_API_KEY` is consumed by legacy `gemini` and accepted by PDD as an `agy` compatibility bridge by mapping it to `GOOGLE_API_KEY` for the subprocess. Provider-level `_has_api_key("google")` returns True if any of the three is set (used for backward-compatible provider-level checks); the per-CLI `_has_cli_api_key(cli)` helper gates on the correct subset: `agy` checks `GOOGLE_API_KEY | ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY | GEMINI_API_KEY`, `gemini` checks `GOOGLE_API_KEY | GEMINI_API_KEY`. Use `_has_cli_api_key(cli)` in `_build_rows()` (the `has_key` field for each CLI row) so the selection table does not mark the `gemini` row as key-configured when only `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` is set, while still keeping existing `GEMINI_API_KEY` users working with `agy`. `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY["google"]` and Google CLI save prompts default to `GOOGLE_API_KEY`, the only key accepted by both binaries. `_displayed_google_key(cli)` shows whichever usable key is already set for the selected CLI, defaulting to `GOOGLE_API_KEY` when none is set.

6.5. OpenCode provider: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY["opencode"]` is `None` because OpenCode reuses provider-specific credentials rather than an OpenCode-specific API key. `_has_api_key("opencode")` returns True only when at least one underlying provider credential environment variable is set. Build `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS` from the non-empty `api_key` values in `pdd/data/llm_model.csv` (split pipe-delimited fields) and include known OpenCode-compatible extras such as `GITHUB_TOKEN`; do not hardcode only Anthropic/OpenAI/Gemini/OpenRouter. `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS` represents environment-variable credentials only; it cannot and MUST NOT be used to represent catalog rows with no `api_key` value, local providers, or other no-key providers. Local/no-key support is handled by parsed OpenCode auth/config semantics in `_has_provider_oauth("opencode")`, not by `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS`.

   `_has_provider_oauth("opencode")` parses `~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json` when present and returns True only when it contains non-empty provider credentials. It also parses OpenCode JSON/JSONC config sources (`~/.config/opencode/opencode.json`, nearest project `opencode.json`, `OPENCODE_CONFIG`, or `OPENCODE_CONFIG_CONTENT`) and returns True only when the parsed config declares a usable selected `model`/`provider` pairing backed by a resolvable credential (`options.apiKey`, `{env:...}` with a set env var, `{file:...}` with a readable non-empty file) or by explicit local/no-key provider semantics. Bare config file existence, valid config containing only preferences, and non-empty `OPENCODE_CONFIG_CONTENT` without a usable provider/model MUST NOT make credential status green. `OPENCODE_MODEL`, `OPENCODE_AGENT`, and `OPENCODE_VARIANT` are not credentials and must not make the key status green by themselves.

7. Module-level constants: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, `CLI_PREFERENCE`, `SHELL_RC_MAP` exposed for use by other modules. Extend `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, and `CLI_PREFERENCE` to include `opencode`; `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY` must be typed as `Dict[str, Optional[str]]`. Display string is `"OpenCode CLI"`; CLI preference remains the public default order (`["claude", "codex", "agy", "gemini", "opencode"]`) so Issue #1318 does not silently make Codex win just because `codex login` exists. CLI preference also lists the Antigravity CLI (`agy`) immediately above the legacy Gemini CLI (`gemini`) — both map to the `google` provider — so the table reflects PDD's binary preference order during the migration. `PROVIDER_DISPLAY["google"]` should label the row as the Google (Gemini family) provider when both binaries are present so users see the rollback option.

% Dependencies

